# Async Programming â³

## Synchronous
Code runs line by line. If one line takes 5 seconds, everything waits.

## Asynchronous
Long tasks start, and code continues running. The task notifies when done.

```javascript
console.log("Start");
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Delayed");
}, 2000);
console.log("End");

// Output: Start -> End -> Delayed
```

# Promises ðŸ¤ž

An object representing a future value.

```javascript
const fetchData = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  // Simulating network request
  let success = true;
  if (success) resolve("Data loaded");
  else reject("Error loading");
});

fetchData
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

# Async / Await âš¡

Syntactic sugar for Promises. Makes async code look synchronous!

```javascript
async function getData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("Something went wrong");
  }
}
```

- `async`: Helper keyword for functions
- `await`: Pauses execution until Promise resolves
